snippet.textDisplay:
Prenuptial agreements and no disclosures are probably “good business” in a marriage or any partnership that involves joint wealth and property. I think the trick is to act with genuine fairness, empathy and respect for BOTH partners or spouses. That’s where these agreements often fall short.

It’s probably easier if both parties have their own (more or less equal) wealth. In the case of wealth imbalance, there’s often more ambivalence. The rich/er partner doesn’t want to be financially screwed. The poor/er partner doesn’t want to be thrown naked into the streets. BOTH concerns are valid. It becomes even MORE VALID if the relationship ends through no fault of the exploited/abandoned partner.

Another thing. Life and fortune are uncertain. A relationship may begin with 1 partner richer than the other and end with the originally poorer partner becoming wealthier.

When drawing up these agreements, people need to think beyond wealth/assets protection and consider what is fair and reasonable in the worst case scenario.

snippet.textDisplay: It’s only shady in THIS situation because if they break up she’s been paying bills for a place she will no longer have. The whole reason he wants a prenup before marriage IS BECAUSE she’s moving in with him. But if she had her own place he wouldn’t have gotten one yet, and so since she’s now spending her money on something WITH HIM... the prenup will prevent her to “own” half of the apartment still if they break up.... that’s the only reason why it’s shady. Its also the whole reason why you have to be evicted from a place after just being there for a full month (I think a month is the correct time)... like let’s say u asked to crash at a friends house one night..... but end up staying there for a month? After a certain amount of time goes by..... the person legally/technically LIVES there... and so the owner of the place (her friend in this scenario) would have to actually evict her, if she wanted her out at that point. And it’s a thing because.... once someone has a place to call home? And then something happens? Their well being is then at stake. Which again... is why the guys prenup for moving in was shady.... the girlfriends well being will then be at stake if they break up because she now has NOTHING and no place to live. So I totally agree with what Tamera said... 1000%. It would need to be made equally. And each pay 50/50. And then also with jeannie, I agree to have your own lawyer look at the prenup and then see if slight changes can be made to protect her if they break up. My solution would be...... if they break up. She can still live there for like two months until she can figure out a plan of where to live next. and I say two months and that may seem long... but think about it. She’s used to a life where she’s paying only HALF of bills with a person. So if they break up she will have to start paying for everything again. And the FULL amount for a new apartment. And so two months can give her time to either start saving up, searching for cheaper places.. and just figuring stuff out. That’s also why when marriages end... the one making more has to pay... because people’s well beings are at stake. Once a person is used to a life a certain way.... you can’t just kick them to the dust and say “figure it out”. They need help until they can get back on their feet again. I also want to say I’m coming at this with having a boyfriend who has to pay child support. So I’m on board with money being taken away if it’s to benefit someone. I just wanna make sure it’s always beneficial to everyone involved at the same time! So yeah! That’s my two cents 😄😄😝

snippet.textDisplay: Yep PRENUPS AND NDA WILL BE YOUR BESTFRIEND IF THINGS DON'T WORK OUT.  My Godmother got one and her and my Godfather divorced after 26 years. He left with what he had and she kept hers and anything they made together went to their 5 kids. NDA is a bonus, especially if you have a  job where you are known to alot of people.  Lawyer, Doctor,  mayor's office, etc. PROTECT WHAT'S YOURS.
